Linux Commands

# $ pwd

/d/Projects

# $ ls

Flask-Web-App/ LearnLinux/

# $ cd LearnLinux/

# $ ls

# $ mkdir folder

# $ ls

folder/

# $ cd folder/

# $ touch file.txt

# $ cat file.txt

Hello

# $ cp file.txt new_file.txt - Copy Command

# $ cat new_file.txt

Hello

# $ mv new_file.txt another_file.txt - Move or rename a file

# $ ls

another_file.txt file.txt

# $ touch commands.txt

# $ rm another_file.txt

# $ less file.txt - view the contents of a file one screen at a time

# $ head file.txt

Hello

# $ tail file.txt

Hello

# $ ls -l - Shows all the read and write permissions

total 1
-rw-r--r-- 1 Lenovo 197121 0 Nov 16 18:49 commands.txt
-rw-r--r-- 1 Lenovo 197121 5 Nov 16 18:46 file.txt

# $ touch first_script.sh

# $ ./first_script.sh

Nancy

# $ ls -l first_script.sh

-rwxr-xr-x 1 Lenovo 197121 25 Nov 16 19:10 first_script.sh\*

# $ df - display disk space usage of file systems.

Filesystem 1K-blocks Used Available Use% Mounted on
C:/Program Files/Git 240751612 159832192 80919420 67% /
D: 90164104 68927088 21237016 77% /d

Filesystem Size Used Avail Use% Mounted on
/dev/sda1 50G 20G 30G 40% /

Filesystem: Name of the file system (device name or partition).
Size: Total size of the file system.
Used: Disk space already used.
Avail: Free disk space available.
Use%: Percentage of used disk space.
Mounted on: Mount point of the file system (where it is accessed in the directory tree).

# $ nproc

12
$ nproc: Executes the nproc command in the shell.
Output: 12
This means your system has 12 logical CPUs (threads) available for processing tasks.

# free - to get free memory on the disk - works in full linux system not in git bash

